		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    The Joys of Roleplaying.</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:"></a> | 
		            4/13/2000 3:07:21 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">OK, correct me if Im wrong, but I do believe this is an RPG. A roleplaying game. However roleplayers are few and far between. This is because of the race for level 50. Ridiculous if you ask me, what good is level 50 if you didn't have fun getting there. And here starts the &quot;guide&quot;.<BR>
<BR>
OK, first off, in my experience, it is most fun to roleplay evil races (Dark Elf, Ogre, Troll). While Dark Elves are fun, I find Trolls and Ogres to be most entertaining. Their lack of intelligence and need to &quot;barsh tingies&quot; makes them most enjoyable. I've found -- at least on my server -- that these are the most commonly roleplayed races.<BR>
<BR>
First and Foremost:<BR>
Speak like your character. A Troll speaking like a rocket scientist doesn't make much since, nor does a High Elf talking about bashing things into little pieces.<BR>
<BR>
Second, and least benificial:<BR>
Play your character like a real (troll, ogre, wood elf etc.). Lets face it, how often will you see Dark Elves and High Elves partying? While this severely limits you (especially as an evil race), it can be more fun and offer a nice challenge. I will admit it, I as my Troll did group with a Gnome. But I made sure he was a Necro, therefore evil and a little more accepted by my character. It also made for interesting conversation as he was also a roleplayer, and if you've ever encountered a roleplaying Gnome, you know how they are....<BR>
<BR>
Third:<BR>
Try to create a backround for your character and make him/her act accordingly. If, say, his/her parents were slaughtered by Gnolls, he would have an uncontrollable ragewhen encountered by one, no matter how high/low a level, and may have to be dragged out by commrades (this is when emotes come in handy :)<BR>
<BR>
Last but not least:<BR>
A big part of roleplaying is friendships. Things like taking a young adventurer of same race/class under your wing and helping him, or choosing to hunt only with a specific set of people.<BR>
<BR>
Note: If you get rude reactions for roleplaying, give the person a tell explaining your stance, but don't be rude. Everyone has a different style of play, and, while yours may seem more suitable (again I mention the online R-P-G) to the game, their style is part of their right. They pay their 10 bucks a month too.
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
