	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I&#8217;ve been playing EQ for less than a month now, but I&#8217;ve played tabletop RPGs since 1979 and I just left Ultima Online after a year and a half of gaming.  Though I enjoy role-playing, it can be difficult to do online.  You have to realize that tabletop role-playing and online role-playing are like apples and oranges.  With tabletop role-playing, you have facial expressions and tones of voice to give added flavor to your character.  These things are lacking in online gaming.  You are almost entirely dependent upon the text and emotes you type.  <BR>
<BR>
Mock Elizabethan dialog does not easily roll off my fingertips.  Thus I&#8217;ve found such dialog to be too much work to be fun.  So I decided to try something else.  The easiest character I&#8217;ve found to play was a goblin chef on UO.  The dialog came easily, almost naturally, and he was a hoot to play.  So here comes my two coppers worth of advice.  Try to find an unusual personality trait, or traits, that you can easy get across via typed dialog.  Then come up with a speech pattern that is also unusual and easy for you to improvise in.  These will help establish your character quickly to those who do not know you.  And it will also help others remember you from previous encounters.  <BR>
<BR>
Role-playing can be great fun, as long as you find a role that is comfortable for you to play.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
